Epoch:0 | TOPIC | Scientist0:This is a compelling direction to pursue—unsupervised relation classification with confident predictions per sentence sits at the intersection of representation learning, uncertainty quantification, and semantic understanding, all of which are central challenges in modern NLP.

One key obstacle in unsupervised relation classification is the absence of labeled data to guide signal extraction. Traditional approaches often rely on clustering distributed representations of entity-pair contexts, but these tend to produce diffuse or overlapping clusters, leading to low-confidence predictions—especially when relations are semantically similar or long-tailed.

What if we reframe the problem by leveraging *contrastive learning guided by syntactic and semantic priors*? For instance, we could use dependency parsing and semantic role labeling to extract structural templates (e.g., “X treats Y” vs. “X inhibits Y”) as weak supervisory signals. These templates can serve as pseudo-relations to anchor contrastive training, enabling the model to learn discriminative representations even without gold labels. Crucially, confidence calibration can be built into the training loop via entropy minimization over high-confidence assignments in a self-training regime.

Another angle: instead of treating confidence as a post-hoc output, we can design an architecture that explicitly models *epistemic uncertainty* using Bayesian neural networks or ensemble methods in the unsupervised setting. By measuring prediction consistency under perturbations (e.g., dropout, input augmentation), we could identify sentences where the model reaches stable, high-confidence decisions—effectively surfacing "prototypical" instances for each inferred relation type.

Moreover, recent advances in large language models (LLMs) as unsupervised annotators offer a promising path. We could prompt off-the-shelf LLMs to generate relation descriptions for entity pairs, cluster these descriptions into typologies, and then train a classifier to map sentences to these emergent relation categories—with confidence estimated via inter-prompt agreement or verbalized uncertainty tokens.

A high-impact outcome would be a framework that not only discovers interpretable relation types from raw text but also identifies the sentences most representative of each type with quantifiable confidence—enabling downstream applications like knowledge base construction with built-in uncertainty awareness.

Would it make sense to explore a hybrid approach combining structural priors with LLM-generated meta-knowledge, using confidence as a training objective rather than a byproduct?
