Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in unsupervised relation classification lies in the absence of labeled data to guide both relation discovery and confidence estimation. Existing methods either assume known relation schemas or rely on heuristics that fail to capture structural coherence across multiple views of text. Inspired by Paper 3’s multi-view inference with uncertain knowledge and Paper 2’s structurally grounded confidence via attention overlap, I propose a novel framework that induces confidence not from labels, but from consistency across syntactically and semantically distinct views of the same sentence. Unlike prior work on OOD detection (Paper 1), which modifies training objectives under supervision, our setting is fully unsupervised—no gold relations are available. The key insight is that confident predictions should emerge when multiple plausible interpretations (e.g., dependency parses, semantic roles, entity-centric contexts) converge on the same relational hypothesis. Furthermore, instead of assuming a fixed ontology, we dynamically induce one using clustering over relation prototypes, guided by cross-view agreement. This creates a feedback loop: high-consistency clusters inform more reliable pseudo-labels, which in turn refine the induced ontology and improve downstream confidence calibration. Crucially, confidence becomes *structurally grounded*—not just a softmax score—but derived from alignment between heterogeneous representations. This differs from Over-MAP’s static overlap measure by being dynamic and bidirectional: structure informs confidence, and confidence shapes structure. It also extends beyond RCL’s contrastive reassignment by operating without any class priors. The result is a self-tuning system where confidence and relation schema co-evolve, enabling robust, interpretable predictions even in low-resource domains.

