  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, Stochastic Multi-View Uncertainty-Aware Relation Learning (SMU-REL), that fundamentally rethinks how confidence is modeled in unsupervised relation classification by integrating uncertainty estimation directly into the multi-view representation process. While prior methods rely on deterministic encodings and measure confidence via downstream consensus, SMU-REL treats uncertainty as a first-class citizen during feature extraction and prototype formation. Our approach introduces three key innovations: (1) Stochastic View Masking (SVM), where each structural view—syntactic, semantic-role, and context-window—is randomly masked during training with learned dropout rates per view type, forcing the model to reason under partial information and thereby exposing fragile predictions; (2) Entropy-Regularized Prototype Matching (ERPM), which computes soft assignments between sentence embeddings and dynamically induced relation prototypes while penalizing low-entropy (overconfident) assignments unless supported by high cross-view stability; and (3) Adaptive Confidence Thresholding (ACT), inspired by OOD detection mechanisms, where class-dependent thresholds are learned online based on the distribution of intra-cluster entropy and inter-view divergence, allowing the model to reject ambiguous or noisy instances instead of assigning spurious high-confidence labels. Crucially, the model maintains a meta-learner that updates the view-specific masking probabilities and threshold parameters based on long-term calibration performance stored in an uncertainty memory bank. This creates a closed-loop system: unstable predictions lead to increased stochasticity and stricter thresholds, promoting conservative behavior until sufficient evidence accumulates. To induce the ontology, we employ a Bayesian nonparametric clustering method (e.g., Dirichlet Process Mixture Models) over relation embeddings, where cluster formation is guided not only by similarity but also by cross-view consistency and entropy minimization within clusters. High-confidence pseudo-labels are then sampled from stable, low-entropy clusters and used in a self-training loop with uncertainty-weighted loss, down-weighting examples whose predicted confidence does not align with observed stability. Unlike existing approaches that treat confidence as a byproduct, SMU-REL makes it a trainable objective, enabling both better-calibrated predictions and interpretable failure modes. The final classifier outputs a relation label, a calibrated confidence score, and a diagnostic trace indicating which views contributed reliably under uncertainty. This framework is particularly impactful for high-stakes domains like clinical text mining or legal reasoning, where knowing *when not to predict* is as important as accurate classification. By embedding uncertainty into the architecture—not just the output—we offer a principled advance beyond heuristic confidence scoring.",
  "Title": "SMU-REL: Stochastic Multi-View Uncertainty-Aware Learning for Calibrated Unsupervised Relation Classification",
  "Experiment": "The implementation consists of four tightly coupled stages: (1) Stochastic Multi-View Encoding: For each sentence, extract syntactic (dependency paths), semantic (SRL frames), and contextual (sliding windows) views. Each view is encoded using fine-tuned BERT variants with view-specific adapters. During training, SVM applies Bernoulli-distributed masking at the view level with learnable retention probabilities optimized via REINFORCE-style feedback from downstream calibration error. (2) Entropy-Regularized Prototype Matching: Relation prototypes are initialized via DPMM on initial embeddings and updated online. Sentence embeddings are matched to prototypes using soft attention, with an auxiliary loss term -λ * H(p) added to discourage overconfident assignments unless cross-view variance falls below a dynamic threshold. (3) Adaptive Confidence Thresholding: A meta-network learns per-prototype thresholds based on historical entropy and consistency metrics from the uncertainty memory bank. Predictions falling below threshold are rejected and excluded from self-training. (4) Self-Training with Uncertainty Weighting: High-confidence, accepted pseudo-labels are used to refine encoders via weighted cross-entropy, where weights depend on both confidence and stability. Evaluation will be conducted on unlabeled splits of FewRel, TACRED, and a biomedical corpus (BioCreative). Metrics include clustering F1, AMI, AUPR for high-confidence predictions, and ECE (Expected Calibration Error). Ablation studies will test SVM, ERPM, and ACT components individually. We expect SMU-REL to outperform URE, CogDL, and the original multi-view baseline in both accuracy and calibration, especially in low-density regions of the relation space.",
